  "heading": "Database Replication",
  "blocks": [
    {
      "mediumHeading": "What is Database Replication?"
    },
    {
      "text": "Database Replication is a technique in which the same data is copied and maintained on multiple database servers."
    },
    {
      "text": "One database is the primary (master) and others are secondary (replicas/slaves)."
    },
    {
      "smallHeading": "Simple definition"
    },
    {
      "text": "Database replication is the process of copying data from one database to one or more databases to improve availability, reliability, and performance."
    },
    {
      "line": true
    },
    {
      "mediumHeading": "Why do we need Database Replication?"
    },
    {
      "text": "Large applications need:"
    },
    {
      "list": [
        "High availability",
        "Fast data access",
        "Backup in case of failure"
      ]
    },
    {
      "text": "**Problems without replication:**"
    },
    {
      "orderedList": [
        "Single point of failure",
        "Slow read performance",
        "Data loss risk",
        "Poor reliability"
      ]
    },
    {
      "text": "ðŸ‘‰ Replication solves these problems"
    },
    {
      "line": true
    },
    {
      "mediumHeading": "How Database Replication Works (Step-by-Step)"
    },
    {
      "orderedList": [
        "Client sends a request",
        "Write operations go to primary database",
        "Primary database updates its data",
        "Changes are copied to replica databases",
        "Read requests can be served from replicas"
      ]
    },
    {
      "line": true
    },
    {
      "mediumHeading": "Components of Database Replication"
    },
    {
  "numberedList": [
    {
      "title": "Primary (Master) Database",
      "points": [
        "Handles **write operations**."
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Replica (Slave) Database",
      "points": [
        "Receives **copied data** from the primary database."
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Replication Log",
      "points": [
        "Tracks **changes** such as insert, update, and delete."
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Replication Process",
      "points": [
        "Transfers **changes to replicas**."
      ]
    }
  ]
},
    {
      "line": true
    },
    {
      "mediumHeading": "Types of Database Replication"
    },
    {
  "numberedList": [
    {
      "title": "Masterâ€“Slave Replication",
      "points": [
        "One master handles **write operations**.",
        "Slaves handle **read operations**.",
        "Most **commonly used** replication method.",
        "**Example:** MySQL replication."
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Masterâ€“Master Replication",
      "points": [
        "Both databases handle **reads and writes**.",
        "Data is **synced both ways**.",
        "Risk of **data conflict**."
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Synchronous Replication",
      "points": [
        "Data is written to **all replicas at the same time**.",
        "Provides **strong consistency**.",
        "Results in **slower performance**."
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Asynchronous Replication",
      "points": [
        "Data is copied **after primary write**.",
        "Generally **faster**.",
        "Slight **data lag** is possible."
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Semi-Synchronous Replication",
      "points": [
        "Uses a **hybrid approach**.",
        "Primary waits for **at least one replica acknowledgment**."
      ]
    }
  ]
},
    {
      "line": true
